    "Striking the right balance requires careful consideration of both the potential risks and benefits of deep learning applications in healthcare, which may necessitate the creation of new regulatory frameworks tailored to the unique challenges posed by this technology [40, [50] [51] [52].",
    "Ensuring the reliability and safety of deep learning models is another significant ethical challenge.",
    "Unlike traditional statistical methods, in which errors may be more predictable and understandable, deep learning models can sometimes produce unexpected and inexplicable errors.",
    "Such errors can have life-threatening consequences [31, 53, 54].",
    "To mitigate these risks, robust procedures should be performed to test and validate the models, monitor their performance in clinical settings, and update them as required to ensure that they continue to perform reliably [55, 56]."
